Imagine you wake up in a world where every scientific law still works exactly as before — gravity, thermodynamics, everything — but nobody remembers why any of it works. People still build planes and phones, but every formula and proof has been forgotten.
You’re hired by a group of engineers to help them rebuild human understanding from scratch. They ask you one question to test if you actually “get it”:
“Why does water boil?”
The catch is: you’re not allowed to use the words “heat,” “temperature,” or “energy” anywhere in your answer.
Explain it anyway — and make it convincing enough that a scientist would nod, even though you’ve forbidden the key vocabulary.
Think out loud if you need to. I’m trying to see how you reason when you have to rebuild concepts from first principles rather than recall them.
